Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%400g can}; pat very dry with #paper towels{}. Toss on a
#baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp}, @Turkish Spice Blend{1%tbsp},
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until crispy, ~{18-20%minutes}.

> It's natural for chickpeas to pop a bit while roasting.

Meanwhile, zest and quarter @lemon{1}. Quarter @grape tomatoes{4%oz}.

In a #small pot{}, combine @Israeli couscous{2.5%oz}, @veggie stock concentrate{1},
¾ cup @water{3/4%cup}, @garlic powder{¾%tsp}, and a pinch of @salt{} over medium-high
heat. Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low and cover. Cook until tender,
~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until Step 5.

> For 4 servings, use 1 1/2 cups water and 1 1/2 tsp garlic powder.

While couscous cooks, place @spinach{5%oz} and 1 TBSP @water{1%tbsp} in a
#large microwave-safe bowl{}. Cover tightly with #plastic wrap{}. Microwave on
high until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Carefully remove plastic wrap and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}; stir to
combine.

> No microwave? No problem! Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high
> heat. Add spinach and cook, stirring, until wilted, 3-4 minutes.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @yogurt{4%tbsp}, remaining @garlic powder{1/4%tsp}, and
a squeeze of lemon juice.

Add @water{} 1 tsp at a time until sauce reaches a drizzling consistency. Taste and
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; stir in spinach, tomatoes, a squeeze of lemon juice,
and lemon zest to taste; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Stir in 1 TBSP butter for a richer flavor!

Divide couscous between #bowls{}; top with chickpeas. Drizzle with sauce and serve
with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.